theorem closure_interior_closure_subset_closure
    {X : Type*} [TopologicalSpace X] {A : Set X} :
    closure (interior (closure (A : Set X))) ⊆ closure A := by
  -- `interior (closure A)` is obviously contained in `closure A`.
  have h : interior (closure (A : Set X)) ⊆ closure A := interior_subset
  -- Taking `closure` preserves the inclusion.
  exact closure_mono h

theorem closure_interior_closure_subset_of_closed
    {X : Type*} [TopologicalSpace X] {A : Set X}
    (hA : IsClosed (A : Set X)) :
    closure (interior (closure (A : Set X))) ⊆ A := by
  -- Because `A` is closed, its closure is itself.
  have hEq : closure (A : Set X) = A := hA.closure_eq
  -- We start from the basic inclusion.
  have h₁ : interior (closure (A : Set X)) ⊆ closure A :=
    interior_subset
  -- Replace `closure A` with `A` using `hEq`.
  have h₂ : interior (closure (A : Set X)) ⊆ A := by
    simpa [hEq] using h₁
  -- Taking closures preserves inclusions.
  have h₃ : closure (interior (closure (A : Set X))) ⊆ closure A :=
    closure_mono h₂
  -- Rewrite once more with `hEq` to obtain the desired statement.
  simpa [hEq, closure_closure] using h₃

theorem closure_interior_closure_subset_closed
    {X : Type*} [TopologicalSpace X] {A : Set X}
    (hA : IsClosed (A : Set X)) :
    closure (interior (closure (A : Set X))) ⊆ A := by
  -- Since `A` is closed we have `closure A = A`.
  simpa [hA.closure_eq] using
    (closure_interior_subset_of_closed (A := A) hA)
